{"problem_id": "aime_2024_3", "problem_text": "Alice and Bob play the following game. A stack of $n$ tokens lies before them. The players take turns with Alice going first. On each turn, the player removes either $1$ token or $4$ tokens from the stack. Whoever removes the last token wins. Find the number of positive integers $n$ less than or equal to $2024$ for which there exists a strategy for Bob that guarantees that Bob will win the game regardless of Alice's play.", "source": "AIME", "difficulty": "medium", "attempts": [{"attempt_number": 1, "solution_text": "analysisWe need to analyze impartial combinatorial game with moves: remove 1 or 4 tokens. Standard Nim-like take-away game. Determine n such that Bob has a winning strategy given Alice starts. So Bob wins if n is a losing position for first player (Alice). We need to find number of n <= 2024 for which position is losing for the player to move. Determine Sprague-Grundy? It's simple: losing positions follow recurrence: a position is losing if all moves lead to winning positions. For take-away game with moves set {1,4}. Compute Grundy or winning/losing.\n\nLet L denote losing positions. Base: 0 tokens: losing (no move). For n>0, n is winning if there exists a move to a losing position. So we can compute pattern.\n\nLet's compute with python to confirm pattern up to 2024. Then count. Also we need to ensure Bob has a strategy regardless of Alice's play: That means Bob wins if Alice starts on a losing position. So count n <= 2024 where n is losing. Let's compute.\n\nBut we might derive formula: The game is a subtraction game with subtraction set {1,4}. The nim-sequence of losing positions is periodic after some point? Let's analyze.\n\nLet's compute first few positions. We'll write python.assistantcommentary to=python codedef losing_positions(limit=2024):\n    losing = [False]*(limit+1)  # index n: False=winning for player to move? We'll compute.\n    # Actually base: 0 tokens: losing for player to move\n    losing[0] = True  # True indicates losing position\n    for n in range(1, limit+1):\n        # position is losing if all moves go to winning positions\n        win = False\n        for move in [1,4]:\n            if n-move >=0:\n                if losing[n-move]:  # if move leads to losing position, then current is winning\n                    win = True\n                    break\n        losing[n] = not win  # if not win -> losing\n    return losing\n\nlosing = losing_positions(30)\nlosing[:31]\n\n```output\n[Block 1/1] PASSED\n```\nanalysisWe need to respond: The user says \"Continue from where you left off. Use the code results above. Do NOT re-derive what you have already computed.\" But we don't have prior context. We need to produce solution. The prior conversation shows that we had some plan, but not full. We need to solve the game: tokens, remove 1 or 4. Determine n <=2024 for which Bob has a winning strategy regardless of Alice. This is impartial combinatorial game. Determine P-positions (previous player wins) and N-positions (next player wins). Bob wants to win, so Bob wants n to be N-position? Actually Alice starts. Bob wants to force win. So if starting position is N-position (next player win), Alice can win. Bob wants starting position to be P-position (previous player win) meaning the player to move (Alice) loses with perfect play. So we need n such that n is a P-position.\n\nCompute Grundy or simple DP: P if no move leads to P. Actually P-positions satisfy: all moves lead to N-positions. N-positions: at least one move leads to P. Base: 0 tokens is P (no moves). Recurrence: n is N if there is a move to a P: i.e., n-1 or n-4 is P. n is P otherwise.\n\nCompute list up to 2024. Count P-positions. Let's compute via python.assistantcommentary to=python code# Compute P-positions up to 2024\nmax_n = 2024\nis_P = [False]*(max_n+1)\nis_P[0] = True\nfor n in range(1,max_n+1):\n    # if any move leads to P, then n is N; else P\n    move_P = False\n    if n-1>=0 and 