each such number is a prime power. Also we can check that all prime powers up to that bound satisfy property.\n\nWe need to produce final answer.\n\nLet's produce reasoning:\n\nLet n be composite with divisors d1=1<d2<...<dk=n.\n\nWe need to show that if n has at least two distinct prime factors, property fails.\n\nWe can analyze the smallest nontrivial divisor d2. Let p be the smallest prime dividing n. Then d2 = p. Next divisor d3 is either p^2 or the next prime factor q>p. We need to consider cases.\n\nCase 1: d3 = p^2. Then we need p | p^2 + d4. So p | d4. But d4 > p^2. Since p divides d4, d4 must be at least p^2 * something. But we can analyze further. Actually we need to check property for i=2: d2 divides d3 + d4. So p | p^2 + d4 => p | d4. So d4 is a multiple of p. But d4 > p^2. So d4 >= p^3. But then we need to check next property for i=3: d3 divides d4 + d5. So p^2 | d4 + d5. Since d4 is multiple of p^3, d4 = p^3 * m. Then d4 + d5 must be divisible by p^2. Since d4 is divisible by p^3, d4 mod p^2 = 0. So d5 must be divisible by p^2. But d5 > d4 >= p^3, so d5 >= p^4. Continue. This suggests that all divisors are powers of p. So n must be a power of p. So if n has at least two distinct prime factors, property fails.\n\nWe need to show that if n has at least two distinct prime factors, then d3 cannot be p^2 because then we get infinite chain requiring all divisors to be powers of p, but n has other prime factor. So contradiction. So d3 must be the next prime factor q. Then we need to check property for i=2: p | q + d4. Since q is prime > p, q mod p != 0. So d4 must be congruent to -q mod p. But d4 is a divisor > q. We can analyze but likely fails.\n\nAlternatively, we can show that if n has two distinct prime factors, then property fails by considering the first few divisors.\n\nWe can produce a rigorous argument:\n\nLet n be composite with at least two distinct prime factors. Let p be the smallest prime dividing n. Then d2 = p. Let q be the next divisor after